properties.name: Conklin Quarry
properties.description: Quarry is in Devonian bedrock overlain by ~20m of pre-Illinoian glacial deposits mantled by ~6.4 m of late Wisconsin loess. properties.name: Wilcox Lake
properties.description: Surrrounding vegetation: white spruce, eastern hemlock, white pine, red pine, eastern white cedar and tamarack, red maple, silver maple, sugar maple, red oak, white oak, burr oak, balsam poplar, trembling aspen, large-tooth aspen, white ash, black ash, blue ash, green ash, basswood, paper birch, pin cherry and black cherry. he native wildflowers include purple coneflower, yellow coneflower, flat-topped aster, heath aster, smooth aster, silky aster, ox-eyed susan, black-eyed susan, bluebeard lily, wood lily, trout lily, common strawberry, common milkweed, blazing star, fireweed, star flower, wild columbine and wild bergamot. Aquatic vegetation that is native to the lake itself include bulrushes, cattails, water arums, water plantains, water lilies, arrowheads, blue flag irises, smartweeds and pickeral weeds. Native shrubs found around the lake include speckled alder, smooth serviceberry, Allegheny serviceberry, nannyberry, red osier, gray dogwood, silky dogwood, broad-leaved meadowsweet, swamp rose, spicebush, buttonbush, shining willow, slender willow, black willow and pussywillow.

properties.name: Joe River Transect
properties.description: Site is a transect ~330 m long, extending away from the Joe River, beginning at the edge of the mangrove fringe and extending into the marsh. The edge of the Joe River is lined with a fringe of Rhizophora and occasional Avicennia, while the interior portions are dominated by Conocarpus associated with Laguncularia, Sabal and several species of hardwood trees and vines. Near the edge of the forest numerous ponds are formed in the dissected surface of the marsh. Here Cladium and ferns appear to be growing under adverse conditions on a higher level provided by remnant pillars of peat, suggesting a recent lowering of the original surface by erosion. Further into the marsh fewer ponds are encountered and growth of Cladium is more vigorous.

Turner Farm [29.9]
properties.description: The Turner Farm site is located on North Haven Island in Penobscot Bay... Like most of the 153 recorded prehistoric archaeological sites on the Fox Islands, the Turner Farm site is a shell midden situated on a relatively level terrace facing a gravel beach... The Turner Farm site is in a protected location facing Fox Islands Thorofare (Figure A5.3). The site is on a terrace and eroding bluff at the northern end of a small gravel barrier beach between Fish Point and Kent Cove. Modern environments include a fresh to brackish back-barrier marsh, sand and gravel barrier, and eroding bluffs of glacial sediment sitting on a bedrock ledge. Tidal flats containing Mya arenaria exist within 1-2 km NW and N of the site today, but the immediate intertidal area is a relatively steep, coarse-grained beachface. (Bourque 1995)

properties.description:
The fossil bearing strata of the Saltville Valley are located in the southwestern tip of Virginia.
Sediments consist of loosely packed Quaternary alluvium composing eight different stratigraphic units ranging in age from upper Holocene to ~27,000 ka (McDonald, 1984). The units are primarily fluvial and lacustrine in origin and suggest periodic transitions between moist swampy areas and drier fluvial systems as evidenced by cycles of peaty muds and silty–sandy clays. The vegetation varied from sedge meadows and alder swamps to pine and spruce forests (Ray et al., 1967; McDonald, 1984). [The city of Saltville lies within two counties, Smyth and Washington. With the lack of a close up map of the region, the coordinates are rough.]

properties.name: Brackloon Lough
properties.description: The site occurs in Brackloon wood, Co. Mayo. It consists of a circular area, about 30m in diameter, of willow swamp dominated by Salix cinerea. The site contains small areas of open water and during heavy periods of precipitation the entire area becomes flooded. Filipendula ulmaria, Angelica sylvatica, Potentilla palustris, Cardamine pratensis and sedges are abundant on the swamp and together with willow form a mat of floating vegetation. The swamp is surrounded by open woodland and scrub which contains Picea sitchensis, Quercus petraea, Fagus sylvatica and Betula pubescens and a thick undergrowth of Rubus fruticosus and Pteridium aquilinm.

properties.name: Harney Peak Pond 1

A few Pinus ponderosa also occur. P. ponderosa dominates the regional vegetation. Pinus flexilis occurs on Harney Peak, but is rare.

properties.name: Bubbling Spring
properties.description: This spring is indeed a 'bubbling' spring in that assumed CO2 degassing is occurring at such a rate that there is an effervescence in the vent area. Watercress is the dominant plant in the spring and limestone outcrops in the area. The spring is surrounded by undeveloped woodland. Its temperature of 12.5 °C suggests that it is recording mean annual air temperature.

properties.description: The mire fills a depression in a slope of ill-sorted boulders which extends from the moraines down to Keglsugl airstrip at 2470m. Lies about 100 m north of Pengagl Creek and consists of a shallow, sloping hollow with a small basin near the SE end. Origin of depression not known. The drainage is by small stream. Surrounded by Lower Montane Forest.

properties.name: Sundown Swamp
properties.description: Interdunal Melaleuca ericifolia swamp. Physiography: Coastal plateau with dunes. Surrounding vegetation: Epacris- Leptospermum heath.

properties.name: Titusville
properties.description: The site is located 1.7 km northeast of the Drake Oil Well historic site and 2.5 km southeast of Titusville, on the south valley wall of Pine Creek, Venango County, Pennsylvania (41°36'58''N 79°38'22''W.; elev. 365 m; Titusville South PA, 7.5' quadrangle) in the glaciated portion of the Allegheny Plateau.

properties.name: Brampton
properties.description: The site is a drained kettle hole exposed during quarrying for gravel

properties.name: White Mesa Mine
properties.description: Locality is a gypsum mine, southwest of San Ysidro in Sandoval County, north-central New Mexico. There were at least 44 fissures within 100 m of the fossil site, and three contained fossil bones. These three fissures were found within a radius of about 15 m with fossil material found at 9-12 m below the the present land surface.

properties.name: White Mesa Fissure 2
properties.description: Locality is a gypsum mine, southwest of San Ysidro in Sandoval County, north-central New Mexico. There were at least 44 fissures within 100 m of the fossil site, and three contained fossil bones. These three fissures were found within a radius of about 15 m with fossil material found at 9-12 m below the the present land surface.

properties.name: Sheep Rock Spring [24JF292]
properties.description: Site is located on Bull Mountain northeast of Whitehall, MT. The Golden Sunlight Mine is also nearby.

properties.name: Raven Camp
properties.description: The author's sparse description of the site does not provide a lot of information that could be used to define the site type as outlined in the FAUNMAP documentation. He simply states the site is located in eastern California's White Mountains, and mentions evidence of foundations for buildings long with deep excavations, where applicable.

properties.name: Havens [32EM1]
properties.description: Along the east shore of Lake Oahe, Emmons County, North Dakota.

properties.name: Umiakoviarusek
properties.description: The site is a Sphagnum bog on a raised palsa mound.

properties.name: Picture Cave
properties.description: Picture Cave is a cave located in the Hueco Mountains within El Paso Co., TX. Current vegetation is Chihuahuan desert scrub.

properties.name: Strathcona Fjord Beaver Pond
properties.description: Early Pliocene peat deposits from Central Ellesmere Island near Strathcona Fiord. Interpretted as being a Beaver Pond environment located in an open larch woodland, near the tree line of the time.

properties.name: Crooked Forks
properties.description: The author's sparse description of the site does not provide a lot of information that could be used to define the site type as outlined in the FAUNMAP documentation. He simply states the site is located in eastern California's White Mountains, and mentions evidence of foundations for buildings long with deep excavations, where applicable.

properties.name: Overmyer
properties.description: A drainage ditch that borders an agricultural field. Part of the Robert Overmyer farm, about 14 km northwest of Rochester, Indiana. Located in Richland township, Fulton county, Indiana, USA.

properties.name: Mosbeck
properties.description: The fossiliferous deposits accumulated in a lagoon that formed between a sand spit and the strandlines of Lake Agassiz. The deposits are associated with the Moorhead Low Water Phase of Lake Agassiz.

properties.name: Campbell CBI
properties.description: The site is located 1.5 km SSW of Judique South on the coast of St. Georges Bay, Cape Breton Island.

properties.name: Seibold
properties.description: The site is a 100m-diameter depression located on the stagnant moraine of the Missouri Coteau.

properties.name: Presumpscot Fm.

properties.name: West Mabou Site

properties.name: Iztapa
properties.description: Red mangrove (Rhizophora) wetland on the central Pacific coastal plain.

properties.name: Bongards site
properties.description: A large, peat-infilled depression that was drained during the construction of a waste lagoon for the Bongards Creamery in 1977.

properties.name: Johns Lake
properties.description: Section exposed on the west wall of the excavation for the McClusky canal

properties.name: Wedron
properties.description: West wall of Wedron Silica Sand Co. Pit 6 (W1/2, NW1/4, NW1/4, Sec. 16, T 134N, R4E, Wedron quadrangle).

properties.name: Kap København
properties.description: The Kap København Formation consists of shallow marine deposits containing terrestrially-derived organic materials. Outcrops occur about 230 m above Mudderbugt as a result of glacioisostatic and eustatic sea-level changes.

properties.name: Leamington Site
properties.description: The Bondi site is a gravel pit located on a broad hill NW of Leamington, Essex County, Ontario. The hill was an island in a succession of Erie basin gracial lakes.

properties.name: Lollandselv
properties.description: The site is a delta terrace about 50 km south of Coloradodal.

properties.name: Boniface River
properties.description: The site is a small palsa peatland that developed on marine clays 35 km from the Hudson bay coast.

properties.name: Coloradodal
properties.description: The site is a pingo located in the Coloradodal valley in northwestern Jameson Land.

properties.name: Portage-du-Cap
properties.description: The section is a lens of peat and silt underlain and overlain by till exposed in a gravel quarry.

properties.name: Thistle Creek/Gold Run Tephra
properties.description: The Thistle Creek section consists of a 10 m organic-rich silt sequence over gravel. The Gold Run Tephra occurs throughout this unit with an early-Middle Pleistocene age.

properties.name: Short Stop
properties.description: The author states the site is located in eastern California's White Mountains, and mentions evidence of foundations for buildings long with deep excavations, where applicable.

properties.name: Midway
properties.description: The author states the site is located in eastern California's White Mountains, and mentions evidence of foundations for buildings long with deep excavations, where applicable.

properties.name: Eva Creek [AKFAI-VP]
properties.description: Vole teeth and bones and associated plant remains. Fairbanks quadrangle, 15 km west of Fairbanks, east-central Alaska.

properties.name: Lismore
properties.description: The Lismore site is located along Northumberland Strait shore about 10 km southwest of Arisaig.

properties.name: Hirtles
properties.description: The site is located on the shore of the Atlantic Ocean.

properties.name: Guelph Site
properties.description: The section was exposed in a road cut excavated for a railroad underpass. The fossils come from peat that is part of a paleosol interbedded between two tills. . .

properties.name: Ch'ijee's Bluff
properties.description: The site is a cut bank on the south side of a large meander loop on the Porcupine River. The fossiliferous bed is about 14 m from the surface located between upper and lower glaciolacustrine deposits.

properties.name: Point Fortune
properties.description: The section is located in a sand pit located 2.2 km south of the Pointe-Fortune, Quebec.

properties.name: Gage Street Site
properties.description: The site is a drained bog and marl lake in which a section was excavated using a backhoe. The site is now a part of industrial complex.

properties.name: Point Wilson
properties.description: The fossils come from the Sangamonian-aged Whidbey Formation which is exposed near the base of a sea cliff.

properties.name: Chesapeake Bay (MD99-2207)
properties.description: Mainstem of the Chesapeake Bay. Physiography: Atlantic Coastal Plain.

properties.name: Chesapeake Bay (MD99-2208)
properties.description: Mainstem of the Chesapeake Bay. Physiography: Atlantic Coastal Plain.

properties.name: Chesapeake Bay (MD99-2209)
properties.description: Mainstem of the Chesapeake Bay. Physiography: Atlantic Coastal Plain.

properties.name: Chesapeake Bay (PTMC3-2)
properties.description: Mainstem of the Chesapeake Bay. Physiography: Atlantic Coastal Plain.

properties.name: Titaluk River Exposure 1
properties.description: A sequence of Pleistocene alluvium and Holocene thaw-lake sediments exposed in a natural riverbluff exposure on the eastern bank of the Titaluk River at the inner margin of the Arctic Coastal Plain.

properties.name: Titaluk River Exposure 2
properties.description: Holocene thaw-lake sediments exposed in a natural riverbluff exposure on the eastern bank of the Titaluk River at the inner margin of the Arctic Coastal Plain.

properties.name: Fain Ranch Arroyo
properties.description: The site's location is as follows: SE 1/4, SW 1/4, section 31, T15N R1E, on the Fain Ranch (private land) near the headwaters of the Agua Fria River, on private land. It was discovered by A. Jordan. The mammoth material was found in the bottom of an arroyo, about 4 meters deep.

properties.name: Domenigoni Valley
properties.description: Valley located in the SE portion of the Perris Block within the northern Peninsular Range. Bundaries inlcude the Elsinore Fault and San Jacinto Fault. Valley trough is filled with alluvial sediments and paleosols, interpreted as braided stream deposits. Indicated by bedded silts, clays and intercalated with course-grained stream channel sediments. The fluvial sediments unconformably overlie widespread lacustrine sediments

properties.name: Winger [14ST401]
properties.description: The site is a suspected paleoindian kill site (a bone bed) in Stanton County. It is exposed in the bank of Bear Creek, itself a tributary of the Arkansas River.

properties.name: Lang Farm
properties.description: The Lang Farm Site is located near the western- and southern-most extensions of the Lake Michigan lobe of the late Wisconsin Laurentide Ice Sheet. The area is characterized by its system of glacial moraine systems.

properties.name: Glacial Lake Arkona-Bondi Site
properties.description: The deposits that produced the bone here were part of a proglacial subaquatic fan that was deposited in glacial Lake Maumee. This deposit was subsequently only modified by lake currents. The aggregate excavation that uncovered this bone at the Bondi site took place within this fan's surface. Site is located between Leamington and Colchester in Essex County, Ontario.

properties.name: Gittin Down Mountain Cave
properties.description: Site is located about 6.5 miles west-southwest of Stilwel in Adair County, OK. There are 6 different entrances to this cave, which hosts over a mile of horizontal passages. The tooth was found 350 feet from an entrance.

properties.name: Island Ford Cave
properties.description: The cave has a large opening near US Route 60 and Interstate 64, a large front room and smaller subsequent spaces. The cave is a popular location for recreational cave exploring.

properties.name: Devlins Park
properties.description: Former proglacial lake of Pinedale age on Caribou Creek that formed when glacial ice from North Boulder Creek downstream advanced across the valley of Caribou Creek. The lake floor is 14-20 m above present Caribou Creek. Surrounding vegetation: Slopes near the coring site are covered by Pinus contorta forest with Abies bifolia and Picea engelmannii. Populus tremuloides and Pinus flexilis are also present. The basin itself is dominated by Salix, Cyperaceae, and Poaceae.

properties.name: Scarborough Mammoth Site
properties.description: Located southwest of Portland, Maine in a farm pit along a shallow ravine. Exact site location is not provided due to landowner's request, so coordinates given here are for the town of Scarborough, ME.

properties.name: Stewart Bog
properties.description: Alpine bog within a suite of moraines. Surrounding vegetation: Subalpine coniferous forest with Picea engelmannii, Abies lasiocarpa, Pinus aristata, P. menziesii, P. strobiformis, Populus tremuloides, and Juniperus communis.

properties.name: Clarksburg
properties.description: Grey silt bed containing organic materials that occurs at the base of a cut bank on the south side of the Grier Creek. The prefered interpretation is that it was deposited during the middle Wisconsinan Port Talbot Interstade

properties.name: Rainy River RR-54
properties.description: The section is within a gravel pit located about 2.5km northwest of the town of Rainy River. The fossiliferous bed is 0.7m of very ripple-laminated very fine sand and silt. Sediments were deposited during the Moorhead low water phase of Lake Agassiz.

properties.name: Flycatcher Basin
properties.description: One of several small closed basins supporting wetlands located within a large landslide (the Flycatcher Embayment). Surrounding vegetation: Closed-canopy Quercus garryana woodland with Pinus ponderosa. Other trees and shrubs occuring locally are Pseudotsuga mensiessii, Juniperus occidentalis, wild rose, waxberry, Rhus trilobata, Ceanothus cuneatus, and Purshia tridentata. Growing within the basin itself are Cyperaceae, Rumex, Verbascum thapsus, Plantago, and patches of Scirpus and Juncus in wetter areas.

properties.name: Shields Pueblo (5MT3807)
properties.description: Shields Pueblo is found north of Goodman Point Monument in the McElmo drainage (McElmo dome), Northern San Juan River Basin. Site contains 18 high density concentrations of cultural remains, which form a horseshoe.

properties.name: Pit Stop Quarry [NAU QSP locality 897]
properties.description: The site is described as a vertebrate assemblage located in a commercial sand and gravel quarry. This site is 11 km south of Taylor, Navajo County in northeastern Arizona.

properties.name: Wales Site
properties.description: The section consists of woody peat overlying 1.5 m of gravel in a gravel pit located about 1.5 km north of Everett, Ontario.

properties.name: Niguanak Uplands
properties.description: The site is a peat section exposed on the east bank of a thaw lake between the Niguanak and Sikrelurak rivers on the North Slope. .

properties.name: Lantz Site
properties.description: Fossiliferous peat and sandy clay are overlain by a reddish-colored diamicton located in a clay quarry on the south side of Lantz

properties.name: Epem Stream Pool San Luis
properties.description: Stream pool. Aeolian landscape with blowout depressions, parabolic dunes, and alkaline flats. Upland vegetation: saline bottom land shrublands, cold desert shrublands, and salt meadows, with Sarcobatus, Salsola, Atriplex, Sueda, Artemisia, and Poaceae.

properties.name: Rainy River E-13
properties.description: The site is a cutbank on the Rainy River near the mouh of the LaValle River. The organic bearing horizon is a 1.5m thick channel sequence of sandy gravel to silty very fine sand deposited during the Moorhead low water phase of Lake Agassiz.

properties.name: First Spring
properties.description: One of many in a series of springs feeding Ruby Lake.

properties.name: Beaufort FM. Site
properties.description: The Beaufort Formation outcrops on the northwestern valley walls of the Ballast Brook. It consists of cross-bedded fluvial gravel and sand interbedded with silt containing unaltered and uncompressed wood. The age of the Beaufort Formation is uncertain with estimates ranging from Pliocene to Miocene.

properties.name: Makinson Site
properties.description: The section is a peat overlain and underlain by bouldery gravels resting on the Eureka Sound Formation. The peat is estimated to be of interglacial age.

properties.name: Saint - Flavien
properties.description: The site is a peat section excavated from a depression within parabolic dunes. It is located 3.5km southwest of Notre-Dame-du-Sacre-Coeur-d'lssoudun.

properties.name: Ruby Marsh Lake Boat Dock
properties.description: The site lies in the Ruby Valley, a topographically closed basin, bordered on the west by the Ruby Mountains. The lake is now a network of spring-fed marshes and shallow ponds. Upland vegetation is Artemisia steppe.

properties.name: Ruby Mountain Divide Seep
properties.description: Spring at the upper end of Road Canyon in the Ruby Mountains. Vegetation mountain meadows and conifer/aspen groves.

properties.name: Gardner Gulch
properties.description: Spring in Gardner Gulch. Surrounding vegetation conifer forest.

properties.name: Hachihama
properties.description: Sewage disposal plant. Physiography: reclaimed land. Surrounding vegetation: paddy field.

properties.name: Hosoike Moor
properties.description: Moor located on the southwestern slope of Mt. Gorin in the northeastern Chugoku Mountans. Moor a complex of open water with Nymphaea tetragona, Cyperaceae fen, and Sphagnum moorland. Overstory vegetation is Ilex crenata and Symplocos coreana. Upland vegetation around the moor dominatd by Cryptomeria japonica and Larix leptolepis, also deciduous forest with Fagus crenata, Quercus mongolica var. grosseserrata, Sorbus commixta, and Acer crataegifolium.

properties.name: Owl Creek Beds
properties.description: The Owl Creek beds are from 2.9 -3.55 m depth in CORE SMO-65 located between the towns of Timmins, Matheson and Cochrane in northern Ontario. The age is uncertain but probably Mid-Wisconinan or Sangamonian

properties.name: Arrepentimientos
properties.description: The site is locarted in the Cordillera Central near the upper limit of tropical montane cloud forest. It lies on the windward slopes within a concave depression (~10 m in diameter), which hosts a small patch of cloud forest (consisting of Ilex repanda, I. impressus, Weinmannia pinnata, Garrya fadyenii, Miconia sp., and Cyathea sp.) surrounded by monodominant Pinus occidentalis forest.

properties.name: Yamakado Moor
properties.description: Sphagnum moor with Menyanthes in a very small basin. Upland vegetatin Cryptomeria japonica forest with evergreen Quercus. Pinus secondary growth.

properties.name: Kurikigahara
properties.description: Sphagnum moor in a small crater in the Hachimantai Mountains.

properties.name: Makura Moor
properties.description: Sphagnum bog with Ilex crenata in a small basin.

properties.name: Ohnuma Moor
properties.description: Sphagnum moor occupying a volcanic crater on the southeast slope of Mt. Torokawa in the Chugoku Mountains. Fen vegetation dominated by Sphagnum, Ilex crenata, and Carex dispalata. Upland vegetation is secondary forest dominated by Castanea crenata, Quercus serrata, and Pinus densiflora.

properties.name: Orochigahara
properties.description: Sphagnum moor (blanket bog) on a gentle slope.

properties.name: Torihama site
properties.description: Site lies in the Hasu River in the Mikata lowland. Site today surrounded by rice paddies.

properties.name: Ubuka Basin
properties.description: Small basin in the Ubuka sedimentary basin at the western edge of the Chugoku Mountains. Today occupied by rice paddies.

properties.name: Yabitsuyachi
properties.description: Sphagnum moor in a small basin.

properties.name: Kewaunee
properties.description: Section is located along the shoreline of Lake Michigan on a 30-m bluff at the south edge of Kewaunee, Wisconsin.

properties.name: Barter Island
properties.description: A section of peat from near the top of an eroding sea cliff west of the DEW Line Station.

properties.name: Marias Pass
properties.description: The 4.75 m section of volcanic ashes and laminated clayey silts was exacavated in a road cut about 2km south of Marias Pass. The fossils come from laminated clayey silt beneath the Mt. St. Helens Jy ash.

properties.name: Innerkip Site [AhHe-VP]
properties.description: 3.2 km southwest of Innerkip, 4-m high stream cut of right (SW) bank of Timms Creek, East Zorra Township, Oxford County, Ontario. Two tills overlie lacustrine deposts. At the base of the lacustrine sediment is a highly compressed, fossiliferous peat ~40 cm thick from which the fossils were recovered.

properties.name: Grapevine Spring
properties.description: Spring in the Mohave Desert.

properties.name: Grapevine Springs
properties.description: Spring in the Mohave Deseert.

properties.name: Nutella Lake
properties.description: Treeline altitude lake. Surrounding vegetation: Mesic shrub and heath tundra mixture.

properties.name: Port Eliza Cave
properties.description: Raised sea cave on west coast of Vancouver Island; 60 meter long cave; fossil material possibly preserved under subglacial lake.

properties.name: Moulin River
properties.description: Fossils come from 36.8-44.8 m depth in borehole 86-BP-9, in the Chaudière valley about 4.0 km NW of Saint-Gedéon. They are from the Massawippi Fm. which is considered to have been deposited during the St. Pierre interval during the mid- to early Wisconsinan.

properties.name: Grande Coulée River
properties.description: Fossils come from two organic horizons at about 45.7 m depth in borehole 86-BP-F1, in the Chaudière valley about 8.0 km SW of Saint-Martin. They are from the Massawippi Fm. which is considered to have been deposited during the St. Pierre interval during the mid- to early Wisconsinan.

properties.name: Halls Bayou Camp
properties.description: Halls Bayou (or stream) on the coastal plain.

properties.name: Toklat High Bluff
properties.description: The Toklat High Bluff is a cut bank section on the Toklat River. Quaternary sediments overlie the Nenana Gravel of Pliocene age.

properties.name: SRM-1
properties.description: Mangrove-dominated estuarine wetland located on the edge of Ponce de Leon Bay at the mouths of Whitewater Bay and Shark River Estuary in Everglades National Park. Situated in a fringing mangrove forest dominated by Laguncularia racemosa and Rhizophora mangle. Avicennia germinans is also prsent.

properties.name: Upper Pinto Fen
properties.description: Extremently rich fen dominated by brown mosses, especially Tomenthypnum nitens, and Larix on the eastern slope of the Rocky Mountain foothills. Surrounded by Picea forest.

properties.name: Sand Cove Road
properties.description: The section of organic- rich sand and clay with moss peat overlies laminated marine clay on the margins of the Sheldon Point moraine.

properties.name: Clarence Lagoon
properties.description: The site is a section of autochthonous peat within a gravel bed 7km east of Clarence Lagoon and 16 km west of Komakuk Beach Airport.

properties.name: Flitaway Site
properties.description: The Flitaway site is a section of silts and peats excavated in an isolated knoll that is 6m in diameter and 3m in height on the NW margin of the Barnes Ice Cap.

properties.name: Isortoq River Site
properties.description: The site is a 6.5 m thick cut bank section on the south shore of the Isortoq River consisting of detrital overbank deposits.

properties.name: Foraker River
properties.description: The site is a 8 m cut bank section on the Foraker River.

properties.name: Loraff Farm Site
properties.description: The site is a 12m high, east-facing cut bank section on the Whetstone River.

properties.name: Nordick Farm Site
properties.description: The Gastropod Sillts are exposed in an 18m high, east-facong wall of a drainage ditch that enters the Yellow Bank River

properties.name: Bear Flat, Peace River, NE British Columbia
properties.description: Site 'located in an agricultural field below steep bluffs on a gently sloping fan (6% gradient), prograded onto a fluvial terrace in the Peace River valley, and is mapped as a colluvial clay fan of the Taylor soil association' (Hebda et al. 2008). The site lies in a south-facing area of the Peace River valley. Site is also known as Bear Flat.

properties.name: White River
properties.description: The western camel phalanx was recovered in August 2010 by D. Turner and B. Ward in situ from the top of an 8 m high sedimentary exposure composed of five units.

properties.name: The Palisades Site
properties.description: The Palisades Site is within the Nowitna Wildlife Refuge. The site consists of a tall bluff complex, formed from unconsolidated sediments which extend almost 11 kilometers along the southern banks of the Yukon River. Specimens were collected from the Palisades East escarpment, from a slump block.

properties.name: Lilienthal Site
properties.description: The Gunder Member of the DeForest Formation, exposed in the bottom half of a 3.3-m thick cutbank in the southwest side of Mud Creek in Cedar County, Iowa.

properties.name: Cape Blossom
properties.description: Cape Blossom is located at the head of the Baldwin Peninsula in Kotzebue Sound, a large embayment of the Chukchi Sea. The Baldwin Peninsula is a push moraine.

properties.name: Harrison Pass East
properties.description: Apparently from a pond in Harrison Pass Creek, perhaps a Beaver Dam on the east slope of the Ruby Mountains.

properties.name: Awl Site midden
properties.description: The vast majority of the southern Mojave supports Larrea tridentata and Ambrosia dumosa (bursage) desert scrub. At the lowest elevations (50–425 m), vegetation is typically sparse. These elevations include Atriplex hymenelytra (desert holly), Ambrosia dumosa, and Larrea, with associates that include Encelia farinosa (brittle bush), Peucephyllum schottii (desert spruce) and Hymenoclea salsola. (cheeseweed). At ca. 200–1300 m elevations, Larrea dominates with A. dumosa, Ephedra spp. (Mormon tea), Encelia, Lycium spp. (wolfberry), Ericameria cooperi (golden bush), Krameria parviflora (ratany) and Salazaria mexicana (bladdersage) as secondary. components. More mesophytic upland desert shrubs such as Prunus fasciculata (desert almond), Coleogyne ramosissima (blackbrush), Thamnosma montana (desert rue) and Yucca brevifolia (Joshua tree) are also found ca. 1300–1700 m, occasionally at lower. elevations. The nearby Avawatz Mountains (maximum elevation of 1877 m) support sparse stands of Juniperus osteosperma (Utah juniper). Widespread perennial and annual herbaceous plants include Eriogonum inflatum (desert trumpet),Machaerathera tortifolia (Mojave aster), Eschscholzia minutiflora and E. californica (poppy), Cryptantha spp. (borage), Malvastrum rotundifolium (five-spot mallow), and occasional Hesperocallis undulata (desert. lily). Vegetation growing at the infrequent springs and along perennial watercourses includes Prosopis juliflora (mesquite) and Chilopsis linearis (arroyo willow). An Atriplex (saltbush) community occurs on alkali environments of playas and riverine deposits. The introduced Bromus rubens (cheatgrass) and Erodium spp. (heron’s bill) are widespread in the study area

properties.name: Stanton Site
properties.description: A cut bank section on an ephemeral stream that drains into an area of sand dunes located about 6 km southwest of Stanton, North Dakota

properties.description: The vast majority of the southern Mojave supports Larrea tridentata and Ambrosia dumosa (bursage) desert scrub. At the lowest elevations (50–425 m), vegetation is typically sparse. These elevations include Atriplex hymenelytra (desert holly), Ambrosia dumosa, and Larrea, with associates that include Encelia farinosa (brittle bush), Peucephyllum schottii (desert spruce) and Hymenoclea salsola. (cheeseweed). At ca. 200–1300 m elevations, Larrea dominates with A. dumosa, Ephedra spp. (Mormon tea), Encelia, Lycium spp. (wolfberry), Ericameria cooperi (golden bush), Krameria parviflora (ratany) and Salazaria mexicana (bladdersage) as secondary. components. More mesophytic upland desert shrubs such as Prunus fasciculata (desert almond), Coleogyne ramosissima (blackbrush), Thamnosma montana (desert rue) and Yucca brevifolia (Joshua tree) are also found ca. 1300–1700 m, occasionally at lower. elevations. The nearby Avawatz Mountains (maximum elevation of 1877 m) support sparse stands of Juniperus osteosperma (Utah juniper). Widespread perennial and annual herbaceous plants include Eriogonum inflatum (desert trumpet),Machaerathera tortifolia (Mojave aster), Eschscholzia minutiflora and E. californica (poppy), Cryptantha spp. (borage), Malvastrum rotundifolium (five-spot mallow), and occasional Hesperocallis undulata (desert. lily). Vegetation growing at the infrequent springs and along perennial watercourses includes Prosopis juliflora (mesquite) and Chilopsis linearis (arroyo willow). An Atriplex (saltbush) community occurs on alkali environments of playas and riverine deposits. The introduced Bromus rubens (cheatgrass) and Erodium spp. (heron’s bill) are widespread in the study area

properties.name: Lough Doo
properties.description: Lough Doo lies in a realatively sheltered site. Along the southern side a open scrub/woodland occurs with Fraxinus, Salix spp, Sorbus aucuparia, Crataegus monogyna, Prunus spinosa, Acer pseudoplatanus, Populus tremula, Betula pubescens and Ilex. The undulating landscape around the other sides of the lake consists of fertile farmland on drift.

properties.name: Ringarooma River
properties.description: The geology of the main peaks and ranges surrounding the river is composed of Devonian granodiorite with small amounts of intrusive metamorphosed Silurian sediments.Temperate rainforest dominates the valley floor. The study sites were located under Nothofagus cunninghamii closed forest, with Leptospermum lanigerttm very prominent in the understorey.Small trees and tall shrubs of P aspleniifoliiis, A. moschatum, Tasmannia lanceolata and T. monganensis, and tree ferns of Dicksonia antarctica are scattered throughout.

properties.name: Samwel Cave
properties.description: Samwel Cave is located on the eastern edge of the McCloud River of Shasta Lake in the McCloud Limestone.

properties.name: Rio Dell Formation
properties.description: Rio Dell Formation, Eel River Basin, Humboldt County, CA. Units where fossils were recovered bracketed by ash beds, give range of 3.0-2.0 Ma for C. gilmorei and 2.0-1.2 Ma for Callorhinus sp.

properties.name: Tule Creek Village [CA-SNI-25]
properties.description: This site, also called Tule Creek Village, is located in the East Locus of San Nicolas Island. The island is 60 miles off the coast of California. The specimens being discussed in this paper were found in the northeast quadrant of East Locus, and contains two individual dogs thought to be buried at the same time.

properties.name: Amaknak Bridge UNL50
properties.description: Amaknak Island is in Unalaska Bay on an old marine terrace about 2m above present sea level.

properties.name: Ft. Dodge
properties.description: The fossil bed is exposed beneath the Des Moines Lobe till on the wall of a gypsum quarry on the south side of Fort Dodge.

properties.name: Cuckoo
properties.description: Lake site in Kilarney National Park, on Old Red Sanstone bedrock

properties.name: Grizzly Lake
properties.description: Closed basin; no inlet or outlet. Boreal forests dominated by Picea glauca, with Betula neoalaskana and Populus tremuloides. Picea mariana, Alnus viridis and Betula kenaica in the region.

properties.name: Panthertown Creek Bog
properties.description: Site lies in Panthertown Valley within the Blue Ridge Mountains. The mire is adjacent to Panthertown Creek near the middle of the valley. Poor fen with Sphagnum.

properties.name: Yehuin
properties.description: Sphagnum magellanicum bog on distal end moraines in the northeastern foothills of the Andies. Surrounding vegetation: steppe/Nothofagus forest transition with Nothofagus pumilio and N. antarctica.

properties.name: Paso Garibaldi
properties.description: Sphagnum magellanicum bog located in the Nothofagus pumilio-N. antarctica krummholz zone ~100 m below treeline.

properties.name: Big Cypress Bend [End boardwalk "Fak10 endB"]
properties.description: Taxodium swamp. Dominant vegetation: Taxodium distichum, Fraxinus caroliniana, Acer rubrum. Secondary vegetation: Ficus aurea, Quercus laurifolia, Rapanea punctata, Thelypteris sp. Tertiary vegetation: Saururus cernuus, Sabal palmetto.

properties.name: McCall Glacier
properties.description: Upper cirque of McCall Glacier in the eastern Brooks Range. Glacier is polythermal and is rapidly retreating.

properties.name: Lake Isabella Delta
properties.description: An organic- rich deposit from the proximal part of the delta constructed on the west end of Lake Isabelle, about 1.5 km east of the Continental Divide.

properties.name: Lake Isabella Peat
properties.description: A section of peat excavated in a meadow immediately west of the delta on Lake Isabelle, about 1.5 km east of the Continental Divide

properties.name: Two Creeks Forest Bed
properties.description: Exposure in the Two Creeks Forest Bed located in a shoreline cliff near the boundary between Manitowoc and Kewaunee Counties, Wisconsin.

properties.name: Sentinel Butte
properties.description: Limestone cliff. Surrounding vegetation: dominated by L. tridentata. Also present are Parthenium incanum, Prosopis glandulosa,. Aloysia wrightii, Cheilanthes sp., Fendlera rupicola, Abutilon sp., Krascheninnikovia lanata, Nicotiana obtusifolia, Brickellia sp., Aristida sp., Muhlenbergia sp., Bouteloua curtipendula, Elymus elymoides, Gutierrezia sarothrae, Dasylirion wheeleri, Fouquieria splendens, Opuntia engelmannii, Datura sp., Rhus microphylla, Stephanomeria sp., Sphaeralcea sp., and Heterotheca subaxillaris.

properties.name: Coyote Hills
properties.description: Surrounding vegetation: L. tridentata, J. cf. coahuilensis, Flourensia cernua, Parthenium incanum, Dasylirion wheeleri, Fouquieria splendens, Atriplex canescens, Gutierrezia sarothrae, Hilaria sp., Brickellia scabra,. Eriogonum sp. and Senecio sp.

properties.name: Lefthand Reservoir
properties.description: A 1.42m section of sedge peat from a bog located at the west end of Lefthand reservoir

properties.name: Mount Ida Ridge Pond
properties.description: A 0.6 m peat core from a small lake on a tundra plateau 1 km east of the continental divide near Mount Ida. No lat/long was provided for the location which should be considered uncertain.

properties.name: Cordón Serrucho Norte wetland
properties.description: Wetland lies within the North Patagonian fold-and-thrust belt in a narrow longitudinal depression on the southwest facing slope of the mountain range. Surface vegetation Scirpus and Empetrum nigrum with Sphagnum magellanicum hummocks in small areas. Stands of Nothofagus antarctica, Pilgerodendron uviferum, and Fitzroya cupressoides occur around the edges. Post-fire stands of Nothofagus dombeyi and Austrocedrus chilensis occur on slopes above and below the wetland.

properties.name: Nelson River
properties.description: The fossils come from silts of the Nelson River sediments exposed in a bluff section on the Nelson River. The sediments are considered equivalents of the Missinaibi Formation. The age of the Missinaibi Fm. is uncertain but possibly Sangamonian.

properties.name: Raymond Basin
properties.description: Glacial kettle lake underlain primarily by till.

properties.name: McKittrick [Insects]
properties.description: The fossils come from asphalt-impregnated sediments that are probably all of Holocene age. They are not from the same section as the Wisconsinan-aged mammal assemblage.

properties.name: La Poudre LP3 Site
properties.description: 1.54m section of peat exposed in a cutbank on the La Poudre Pass Creek about 2km southwest of the Long Draw Reservoir.

properties.name: Carpinteria [Insects]
properties.description: The fossils come from asphalt that was mined in a quarry located in a marine terrace of middle to late Pleistocene age. The quarry was later used as a landfill and is currently part of Tar Pits Park.

properties.name: Mayo Indian Village
properties.description: The fossiliferous horizon is from near the base of a cutbank section on the north side of the Stewart River about 2.4 km downstream from the Mayo Indian village.

properties.name: Gardena Site
properties.description: The site is a cut bank on a tributary of the Farm Creek about 1km SE of the Farm Creek section. Fossils come from two horizons within the Morton Loess which in the section is overlain by till of the Wedron Formation and is underlain by the Robein Silt.

properties.name: Rock River YT
properties.description: The fossils are from a peat bed within a 32m cut bank section on the Rock River, a tributary of the Bell River.

properties.name: Cuivre River Section B
properties.description: The fossils come from 14.3 m depth in a cut bank section on the Cuivre River, a tributary of the Mississippi River

properties.name: Bonfils Quarry
properties.description: The fossils come from organic stringers near the base of a loess section that overlies the St. Louis Limestone in the Bonfils Terrace on the Missouri River.

properties.name: Bishop's Cap
properties.description: Bishop's Cap is located in Dona Ana County, New Mexico. . Current vegetation at the site is Chihuahuan desert scrub. The substrate is limestone.

properties.name: County Line
properties.description: The fossil site is a cutbank on the County Line Branch of Bear Creek near the border between Hancock and Adams Counties, 3.9 km NW of Lima. The fossils come from a dark gray silt.

properties.name: Woodbridge

properties.name: Slipper Lake
properties.description: Slipper Lake is located approximately 50 km north of mapped treeline in Canada's Northwest Territories. This is a remote. "pristine" lake that is relatively deep with slightly acidic pH (6.4) and a surface area of 1.9 km'. Slipper lake is situated on Canadian Shield bedrock characterized by relatively high amounts of silicon and potassium. and low levels of magnesium and calcium. Acidic granitic-gneissic rock predominate Shield rocks and include gneiss. migmatite. granitoid intrusions and. metamorphosed volcanic and sedimentary. The lake is in the arctic tundra zone characterized by continuous permafrost, and poorly developed soils that consist mainly of cryic regosols. Climate in the area is characterized by cool, dry conditions with a mean January night-time temperature of -37.5°C, mean July day-time temperature of 12.5°C and annual precipitation of 200 mm. Tundra lakes are frozen for most of the year with an average open-water period of 90 days. . More lake data can be found in Chapter 5 of the publication.

properties.name: Colville River
properties.description: The fossils come from near the base of a 30m thick section of unconsolidated deposits overlying about 40 m of Cretaceous bedrock. The section is part of a steep bluff on the lower Colville River located about 19 km north of its confluence with the Anaktuvuk River.

properties.name: Colorado Creek
properties.description: The site was exposed during a placer gold mining operation on the Colorado Creek. The fossils occur in silts associated with mammoth bones located about 2.5 m depth from the surface on the east bank of the creek before it was displaced by mining.

properties.name: Joint Site
properties.description: The fossils come from a midden within ruins of a 13th Century pueblo referred to as the Joint site (NS-605). The site is located about 13km NNE of Snowflake and about 2.5km NW of Point of the Mountain Mesa, Arizona. The local vegetation is a Juniper grassland

properties.name: St. Charles Site
properties.description: The fossils occur in a pre-Farmdalian alluvium near the base of a high cutbank on the Clanton Creek, about 3.9km NNE of St. Charles, Iowa.

properties.name: Lava Camp Mine
properties.description: The fossil bed was exposed during an underground mining operation for placer gold at the Lava Camp Mine located in the upper valley of the Inmachuk River. Fossils of insects, plant maceroscopic remains and wood come from cross-bedded alluvial sand that overlies schists and metasediments and is overlain by a lava flow. .

properties.name: Revenue Creek
properties.description: The fossils come from organic-rich silts interbedded within iron-stained fluvial gravels exposed 10.3 m from the surface during placer gold mining operations.

properties.name: Madelia
properties.description: Drained wetland in a small depression in ground moraine.

properties.name: Salt Spring
properties.description: The fossils come from a core and cut bank sections at the mouth of Spring Creek Hollow, located 5.3 km SW of Hardin, Illinois. The samples, Salt Spring SSHA and Salt Spring A Middle are believed to be from the same stratigraphic horizon even though there are small faunal differences between them.

properties.name: Tyson Spring Cave
properties.description: Solution cavern in the Driftless Area of southeastern Minnesota formed in Ordovician limestoneof the Galena group. Cave is a relatively large, low-gradient, dendritic conduit.

properties.name: Hungry Creek

properties.name: Lost Chicken Site

properties.description: Lake. Physiography: bedrock basin. Surrounding vegetation: Pinus sylvestris, Picea abies, Betula sp.

properties.name: Old Crow CRH 44

properties.name: Old Crow CRH 15

properties.name: Old Crow CRH 32

properties.name: Lake PW03
properties.description: Lake PW03 (73° 07′ N, 96° 41′ W) is located on Prescott Island, a small island of the Prince of Wales Island group, in the central Canadian Arctic Archipelago. Lake PW03 is nearly circular, with a surface area of 9 ha and depth of approximately 9 m. The lake is located on a raised plateau at an elevation of 243 m a.s.l., within a thin outcrop of Precambrian gneiss that runs along the eastern coasts of both Prince of Wales and Prescott Islands. Prescott Island was deglaciated from north to south at approximately 11000 cal. BP. Although lower-lying areas along the coasts of the island were submerged following deglaciation, the elevation of Lake PW03 was above postglacial marine inundation. . Woo and Zoltai (1977) place Lake PW03 in the Prescott Island Uplands ecological district. Vegetation in this district is classified as middle Arctic. The dwarf shrubs Cassiope tetragona and Salix arctica are abundant; sedge meadows and crustose lichens are common. Vegetation cover is greater than 50% in the region of the lake; the crystalline bedrock surrounding Lake PW03 is associated with more luxuriant and diverse vegetation assemblages relative to the nutrient-poor ‘limestone barrens‘ overlying calcareous substrates that dominate much of Prince of Wales and surrounding islands. Limnological information collected on the day of coring using hand-held meters indicates that the lake is nearly neutral (pH = 7.5) and very dilute (specific conductivity = 45 µS/cm). Climatic conditions are severe; mean daily temperatures in the region are −15°C, 4°C and −30°C (annual, July, January). Lake ice begins to thaw in June and refreezes in late August. Precipitation is low in this region, with an average yearly total of 150 mm, the majority of which occurs as snow.

properties.name: Baldwin Peninsula
properties.description: Fossils come from stratified lacustrine sediments exposed in a bluff overlooking Kotzebue Sound about 35km SE of Kotzebue.

properties.name: Lake KR02 (unofficial name)
properties.description: Small lake located in the Kuujjua River region of Victoria Island. Surrounding vegetation: Prostrate shrub tundra composed of Dryas, sedges, grasses, Salix, Artemisia, and several species of Fabaceae.

properties.name: Lake MB01
properties.description: Surrounding vegetation: Prostrate dwarf-shrub-herb tundra. Small prostrate shrubs such as Salix and Dryas, graminoids, forbs, and lichens.

properties.name: SL06
properties.description: Surrounding vegetation: Prostrate shrub tundra dominated by Cyperaceae tussocks mixed with prostrate Salix and other herbs (ie Oxyria, Dryas).

properties.name: Lynn Creek
properties.description: The fossils come from a compressed peat near the base of thick section of gravel on the west valley wall of Lynn Creek which occupies a bedrock canyon. The peat is underlain by till. The gravel is outwash from the Vashon Glaciation. The peats are considered to have been deposited during the Olympia Non-Glacial Interval.

properties.name: Chacra Mesa
properties.description: Chacra Mesa is located in Chaco Canyon NAtional Monument, McKinley Co., NM.

properties.name: Dog Canyon
properties.description: Dog Canyon is in the Sacramento Mountains of Otero County, NM.

properties.name: Fra Cristobal
properties.description: Fra Cristobal is in the Fra Cristobal Mountains of Sierra County, New Mexico.

properties.name: Isleta
properties.description: Isleta is located in the Rio Grande VAlley of Bernalillo County, NM.

properties.name: Igaliku Norse Farm Site
properties.description: Fossils were collected from three sections (A, B, C) of peat within an excavated trench through an early Norse farm settlement in southern Greenland. Fossils come from 20-80 cm depth from the surface.

properties.name: Hueco Mts. RW4028
properties.description: Hueco Mountains RW4028 is located in Hudspeth County, Texas.

properties.name: Croxton; [XHP-311]
properties.description: Tukuto Lake is nestled in the rolling hills of the Arctic Foothills Physiographic Province on Alaska's north slope. The lake is located about 20 miles northwest of Howard Pass proper, in proximity to the confluence of the Etivluk and Nigu Rivers.

properties.name: Castle Mountains
properties.description: The Castle Mountains site is located in the Castle Mountains of Pima Co., AZ near Ventana Cave. . Correspondence from T.R. Van Devender to Emil Haury (08/22/1980): '.The sequence in general is a single-needle pinyon, juniper, shrub live oak woodland in the late Wisconsian to a juniper-catclaw association in the early Holocene to a catclaw brittlebush association in the middle Holocene (Altithermal) to a paloverde saguaro desertscrub in the late Holocene. The surprise in the record is that typical Sonoran Desert communities may have developed quite late and that paloverde may be a late arrival. The catclaw growing on the cliff bases in the Altithermal certainly implies warm, wet conditions'. . At least one very descriptive account of the collection area exists within the original Van Devender handwritten and typed site file: it is for the area surrounding Castle Mountain 3. The narrative is as follows: 'a vertical crevice, at the base of an extensive cliff. There are two small openings in the ciff, each of which house a midden. (upper and lower middens). Samples were taken from both of the middens. The middens did not show heavy signs of amberat, but did appear to show antiquity. Four samples (3 lower and 1 upper midden) were taken and were realatively easily extracted. Sample 3C showed signs of Acacia greggii. There is possibly another midden sample above on a higher ledge that was inaccessible without more equipment. An owl's roost was also visible in the ledge above.' (Collectors are listed as Tony Burgess and Terry Nickerson, but collectors are listed as T. Van Devender and J. Betancourt on the typed collection sheets asociated with Castle Mountain 3. . For the purposes of Neotoma: all collectors were listed as Van Devender and Betancourt Aasen Rylander 2016). . Detailed maps exist within the site file giving locations of major highways, distances from the site to major cattleguards etc.

properties.name: Hueco Tanks
properties.description: Hueco Tanks is located in the Hueco Mountains of El Paso Co., Texas within the Hueco Tanks State Historical Park.

properties.name: Hueco Mountains, TX
properties.description: The Hueco Mountains site is located within Hudspeth County in Texas.

properties.name: Oatman
properties.description: Oatman is a midden collected from a ledge about 30 feet above a wash between Oatman and the Colorado River (taken from the Van Devender and Toolin report on the midden (undated)). The legal location was not given in the report; so the locational data used for Neotoma will be approximate and based on the town of Oatman, AZ. Nootes in the file indicate the site was 'collected from a ledge about 30 feet above a wash between Oatman and the Colorado River. The ledge is in a 60 foot cut incised into an older alluvial fan terrace deposit'. . The latitude and longitude chosen for Neotoma represent a spot half way (due west) between Oatman and the Colorado River.

properties.name: Oliver Bluffs
properties.description: The insect fossils come from a siltstone lens interbedded with tillites in an 80m high section of the Oliver Bluffs on the Beardmore Glacier. The section is immediately south of Plunket Point where the Beardmore and Mill Glaciers converge.

properties.name: Cape Deceit
properties.description: Fossils are reported from three stratigraphic units, from oldest to youngest, the Cape Deceit Fm., the Inmachuk Fm., and the Deering FM. The formations are exposed in 12m high bluffs along a 0.5 km section of shoreline facing Kotzebue Sound. The bluffs are located about 2.5 km NW of Deering, Alaska.

properties.name: Cement Creek Cave
properties.description: Cement Creek Cave, in the Upper Gunnison Basin, is a solution cavity within a discontinuous outcrop of Leadville limestone, (Paleozoic, Middle Mississippian age).

properties.name: Jordan Creek
properties.description: Creek which may no longer exist.

properties.name: Pine Oak Slough
properties.description: Slough

properties.name: Lake Challa Savannah
properties.description: Savanna dominated by Acacia nilotica and A. senegal. Site is located ~500 m northwest of Lake Challa.

properties.name: Abenakis River
properties.description: The fossils come from Massawippi Fm. fluvial silts and sands at 63-67m and 69-73.5m depth in an exploration borehole drilled into placer gold deposits(86-BP-15).

properties.name: Lake Challa Lakeshore
properties.description: Evergreen forest along east shore of Lake Challa with Sorindeia madagascariensis, Ficus sycomorus, and Trichilia emetica.

properties.name: Lake Challa Crater Rim
properties.description: Site is located on the crater rim. The upper part of the inner crater slope is dry forest occurs with succulents such as Euphorbia quinquecostata and deciduous species such as Commiphora baluensis and Haplocoelum foliolosum dominating the tree layer. The outer crater slopes are covered with dry savanna woodlands, with a lower and more open canopy dominated by stunted, fruit tree-like appearance of the woody species mainly belonging to Combretaceae, Burseraceae and Anacardiaceae.

properties.description: Spring - May have been covered.

properties.name: Saylorville Reservoir
properties.description: The section from which the fossils were recovered is in the distal part of the spillway of the Saylorville Reservoir. The section was exposed by floodwaters during 1984 when discharge down the spillway eroded a gorge into the Pennsylvanian bedrock underlying the glacial deposits.

properties.name: Nuyakuk Site
properties.description: The fossiliferous peat occurs near the base of a 6 m cut bank section on the Nuyakuk River about 24 km E of where the river discharges from Tikchik Lake

properties.description: Ultra-oligotrophic with one outflowing river

properties.description: Bennett Ranch is located in Presidio Co., TX. BR 4 and 5 are located along the Rio Grande River.

properties.name: Maxus Site 5
properties.description: The site is an old and partially filled river oxbow. Surrounding vegetation: Evergreen tropical rainforest.

properties.name: Sheep Camp Canyon
properties.description: Sheep Camp Canyon is a rockshelter located just west of Sheep Camp Canyon and facing Chacra Mesa in Chaco Canyon National Monument, San Juan County, New Mexico. Sheep Camp anyon's official legal description is 29SJ178.

properties.name: San Andres Canyon
properties.description: San Andres Canyon is in the Sacramento Mountains of Otero Co., New Mexico.

properties.name: Clys Canyon
properties.description: Clys Canyon is located within Chaco Canyon National Monument in McKinley Co., NM.

properties.name: Quitman Mountains
properties.description: The Quitman Mountains site is located in Hudspeth Co., Texas.

properties.name: Tawny Pond
properties.description: Heavily glaciated region near the northern edge of the Eastern Great Lakes Lowland Forest Region. Cold-tolerant softwoods dominate the forest.

properties.name: Indian Ruins,  NM
properties.description: Indian Ruins is located in Chaco Canyon National Monument in San Juan County, northwestern New Mexico.

properties.name: Big Boy Canyon
properties.description: Big Boy Canyon is located in the Sacramento Mountains of Otero Co., NM. . The latitude and longitude used for Neotoma was taken from Van Devender's computerized data sheets as opposed to the handwritten Van Devender sheets for each samples locations and radiocarbon dates. Hence, latitude is listed as 32 53' and longitude was set at 105 55 (as opposed to 105 54' 30 listed on the handwritten data sheets).

properties.name: Cuchilla La Rabona
properties.description: This section was taken from a peaty soil on the western side of the Eastern Cordillera in the Sumapaz area. Local vegetation was bamboo páramo with Chusquea (Swallenochloa), Senecio, Espeletia, and Lachemilla cf. L. nivalis, with abundant bryophytes.

properties.name: La Teta-2
properties.description: The La Teta wetland is located in the Cauca Valley near the foothills of the Western Cordillera. The mire probably formed within an inflled lake cut off from the main drainage system. Today, the Cauca Valley is presently almost completely deforested and crops of sugar cane dominate. The original vegetation was neotropical dry forest.

properties.name: Rio Timbio
properties.description: The Rio Timbio coring site is located in the southern part of a saddleshaped area which forms a kind of high plain ('altiplanicie de Popayan'). The site is located in a swamp of ~60 m diameter in a small depression, as the coring site has been filled with organic-rich sediments. A small shallow creek crosses the depression from east to west. The catchment area extends only a few hundred meters from the coring site. The natural vegetation of the study area is almost completely replaced by commercial forestry, coffee plantations, and farmland. small patches of possibly secondary forest fringe the rivers. Natural vegetation was humid to very humid low montane forest.

properties.name: Pantano de Vargas 1
properties.description: The surface of the sediments represent the floor of an ancient lake which received water from the Chicamocha River. The palaeo-lake and swamps were drained some 50 yr ago for agricultural development. The gulley of the former Chicamocha River, now a quiet water current, lies several meters below the surface of the lake sediments suggesting that the main stream line in the palaeolake had stabilized for a very long time while the remaining surface of the palaeolake accumulated sediments continuously. The area today is mostly agricultural. Natural vegetation was at the transition from subandean to andean forest.

properties.name: Boquillas
properties.description: The Boquillas core was collected in the town of Boquillas, in the centre of the Momposina basin. Site is located in the centre of the Momposina basin, or 'Depresión Momposina,' a tectonic basin covered with floodplain lakes, locally called 'cienagas.'

properties.name: Hippa Lake
properties.description: Shallow lake on Hippa Island with no inflowing streams

properties.name: Misty Lake
properties.description: Moderate-sized, humic lake, with a small stream that flows through 500m of wetland before entering the lake

properties.name: Port McNeill Bog
properties.description: Flat ombrotrophic bog along a roadside; surface vegetation dominated by ericaceous shrubs, Sphagnum capillifolium and Sphagnum fuscum. Open Pinus contorta bog-woodland surrounds the bog

properties.name: Roe Lake
properties.description: Small lake with no inflowing streams in bedrock depression. Forests surrounding the lake are dominated by Pseudotsuga menziesii, Thuja plicata, and Abies grandis in the canopy, with Acer macrophyllum and A. glabrum present along the lake margin and Gaultheria shallon, Symphoricarpos albus, Polystichum munitum, and Pteridium aquilinum common in the understory. A stand of Alnus rubra is located along the southeastern margin of the lake. Xeric taxa, including Arbutus menziesii and Quercus garryana, are scattered on the adjacent ridges.

properties.name: Pantano de Mónica 1
properties.description: Large swamp located on the lower terrace of the Rio Caquetá. Regional vegetation is dense, tall tropical rainforest, except for savanna on samller areas of sandstone plateaus. Local vegetation is a dense stand of tall trees, primarily Clusia. Mauritia also occurs in the swamp, which also has open water and moss polsters.

properties.name: Pantano de Mónica 2
properties.description: Small swamp located on the lower terrace of the Rio Caquetá. Regional vegetation is dense, tall tropical rainforest, except for savanna on samller areas of sandstone plateaus. The swamp is covered by tall tress (~10 m), mainly Fabales.

properties.name: Pantano de Mónica 3
properties.description: Small hollow basin in a forested area located on the lower terrace of the Rio Caquetá. Regional vegetation is dense, tall tropical rainforest, except for savanna on samller areas of sandstone plateaus. Euterpe is frequent at the site.

properties.name: Qeqertasussuk
properties.description: The fossils come from frozen peaty sediments associated with a paleo-Eskimo settlement: B 32-33 = midden; C9-18 = dwelling. The dwelling and midden are located on a raised beach.

properties.name: Jameson Land
properties.description: The fossils come from 18 samples of detrital organic sediments exposed along 74 km of the Jameson Land coast between Falstersalv and Hesteelv at elevations ranging from 5.7- 47. 0m above msl.

properties.name: Andabobos
properties.description: This section was taken from a level Plantago rigida cushion bog covering a former glacial lake on the western side of the Sumapaz watershed. Vegetation is grass-paramo, with Espeletia-Calamagrostis effusa bunch-grass paramo. Bog surface has Diplostephietum revoluti with Swallenochloa, Sphagnum, and Riccardia.

properties.name: Boca de López
properties.description: Site is located in the Ciénaga Grande De Santa Marta, a low salinity lagoon in the delta of the Magdalena River on the Caribbean Coast. The coring site is located between where the Rio Frio and Rio Sevilla discharge into the lagoon, near the mouth of caño San Joaquin, which is called Boca de López, in 50 cm of water, ~100 m from the mangrove swamp bordering the open water. The dominant mangrove is Rhizophora mangle. Also occuring in the swamp are Acrostichum, Sagittaria, Cyperus, Salvinia, Pistia, Eichhornia, Azolla, and Lemna.

properties.name: Valle de Lagunillas V
properties.description: Valle de Lagunillas contains a series of end moraines with a chain of existing and former lakes. The valley lies west of the main central ridge of the Sierra Nevada de Cocuy. The site a former lake within the area of Drift II as defined by Gonzalez et al. (1965). Surrounding vegetation is páramo, with meadows of Poaceae and with Espeletia as the most characteristic plant.

properties.name: Valle de Lagunillas VIII
properties.description: Valle de Lagunillas contains a series of end moraines with a chain of existing and former lakes. The valley lies west of the main central ridge of the Sierra Nevada de Cocuy. The site is a small basin lying between two end moraines of Drift II as defined by Gonzalez et al. (1965). Surrounding vegetation is páramo, with meadows of Poaceae and with Espeletia as the most characteristic plant.

properties.name: Valle de Lagunillas VII
properties.description: Valle de Lagunillas contains a series of end moraines with a chain of existing and former lakes. The valley lies west of the main central ridge of the Sierra Nevada de Cocuy. The site is a small basin lying between two end moraines of Drift II as defined by Gonzalez et al. (1965). Surrounding vegetation is páramo, with meadows of Poaceae and with Espeletia as the most characteristic plant.

properties.name: Valle de la Bocatoma XI
properties.description: Valle de la Bocatoma is a tributary of Valle de Lagunillas. The valley contains a series of end moraines with a chain of existing and former lakes. Glacial ice lies at its head. The valley lies west of the main central ridge of the Sierra Nevada de Cocuy. The site lies in the valley bottom along a stream behind end moraines of Drift III as defined by Gonzalez et al. (1965). Surrounding upland vegetation is páramo, with meadows of Poaceae and with Espeletia as the most characteristic plant.

properties.name: Last Chance Canyon
properties.description: Last Chance Canyon is located in the Guadalupe Mountains. Current vegetation is Chihuahuan desert scrub and grassland.

properties.name: Roberts Creek
properties.description: The fossils come from a series of cut bank sections on Roberts Creek located 1.40 - 3.18 km NNE of Gunder, Iowa. Roberts Creek is a tributary of the Turkey River

properties.name: Piagua
properties.description: It is a small swampy area, about 100 x 100 m in size, in a depression which is crossed by a small shallow creek draining in a westerly direction. The catchment area of the depression is almost 1 km in diameter. The location lies in the subandean forest belt. The natural vegetation is almost completely replaced by commercial forestry, coffee plantations and farmland.

properties.name: Quilichao-1
properties.description: The Quilichao basin lies on a terrace close to the Cauca River. The Cauca valley is presently almost completely deforested and crops of sugar cane dominate. Natural egetation is tropical dry forest.

properties.name: Páramo de Peña Negra 1
properties.description: This lake is situated at the northwestern periphery of the high plain of Bogota in the Cordillera Oriental. It forms the northernmost part of the eastern main water divide of the Subachoque valley. It is a glacially eroded basin, bounded by a moraine, with a flat bottom and no fluvial inflow. The site is located in the lower grass páramo. The section was taken from the edge of a hummock in the Sphagnum-Swallenochloa tessellata peatbog.

properties.name: Páramo de Agua Blanca
properties.description: The site is a Sphagnum-Espeletia fen formed in a small weathering depression formed in sandstones of the Guadalupe Formation. The site lies at the upper timberline of the andean forest belt. The land is presently being used for cattle and cultivation of potatoes. Locally on the slopes are patches of partly secondary forest, dominated by Weinmannia, Melastomataceae, Asteraceae, and Ericaceae. Other woody taxa include Myrica, Gaiadendron, Vallea, and Oreopanax.

properties.name: Daisy Lake
properties.description: Daisy Lake is a long (3km) and narrow (0.25 km), double basin lake with maximum and mean depths of 14.8 m and 5.2 m, respectively, located 2 km southwest of the Coniston Smelter. Present-day limnological characteristics indicate that the lake is very acidic (pH 4.7), and has highly elevated metal concentrations.

properties.name: Rita Blanca
properties.description: The fossils come from Plio-Pleistocene laminated lacustrine deposits exposed in a section in Mustang Draw about 11 km WNW of Channing, Texas

properties.name: St. Eugene
properties.description: The site is a section in a gravel pit located about 2 km SE of St. Eugene. The fossils come from a lens of organic material within sandy deltaic gravels associated with the Champlain Sea.

properties.name: St. Hilaire
properties.description: The site is a section in a gravel pit located 5 km SE of St. Hilaire. The fossils come from a thin organic bed within marine clays of the Champlain Sea.

properties.name: Rosarito
properties.description: Site is a road-cut exposure that rests on moraine material of the Early Murillo glacial stade. The site lies in the Andean forest zone.

properties.name: Blomidon (North Section)
properties.description: The fossils come from the upper part of a peat bed that was exposed in a roadcut 0.6km NW of Blomidon about 15km N of Wolfville. The peat was underlain by red-colored silty till and silty clay and overlain by a clay and a sand bed up to 2 m thick.

properties.name: Blomidon (South Section)
properties.description: The fossils come from a peat bed that was exposed in a roadcut 0.6km NW of Blomidon about 15km N of Wolfville. The peat was underlain by red-colored silty till and silty clay and overlain by a clay and a sand bed up to 2 m thick.

properties.name: Rosarito Grande
properties.description: Site is a road-cut exposure that rests on moraine material (on block lava) of the Early Río Recio glacial stade. The site lies in the Andean forest zone.

properties.name: Ría Lagartos-2
properties.description: The sampling site is a pond located 3.6 km from the coast. Vegetation around the site is low-stature flooded tropical forest (mangrove swamp) with Conocarpus erecta, Haematoxylum campechianum, Plumeria sp., Thrinax radiata, and Cyperacae. Aquatic vegetation consists of Cladium jamaicense, Poaceae, and Typha.

properties.name: Llano Grande Mire
properties.description: Site is located in the Llano Grande basin which is part of the Páramo de Frontino, the largest tropical montane grassland in the Western Cordillera of Colombia. The site is located at the upper forest line.

properties.name: San Bernardino Cienega
properties.description: San Bernardino Cienega is located in the Sonoran Desert, but near the ecotone of the Chihuahuan Desert grassland. Currently the cienega surface is dry except for a few artificial impoundments and small perennial springs.

properties.name: Kvichak Peninsula
properties.description: The fossils come from peat and silty peat from two horizons exposed in a 9m high section facing Kvichak Bay near Lake Point. The lower horzon is assiged to the Flounder Flat complex and the upper one the Eltolin complex. The Flounder Flat complex overlies glacigenic deposits and the Etolin complex is overlain by loess. The deposits are Mid-Wisconsin to Sangamon age.

properties.name: Tip Top, Sierra Co., NM
properties.description: The Tip Top site is located in Sierra Co., New Mexico in the San Andres Mountains. The site is discussed along with other midden sites from New Mexico's San Andres Mountains in Betancourt et al.'s (1990) publication where records from the Sacramento Mountains and the Hueco Moutains are also detailed and compared. . A plant list compiled by Van Devender and Toolin (11/5/1982) of current vegetation is located within the site file stored with the Neotoma middens in the repository.

properties.description: Spring

properties.name: Unnamed Spring
properties.description: Spring

properties.name: Old Crow Basin
properties.description: Sample from in and around a thaw pool

properties.name: Tuktoyaktuk Peninsula
properties.description: Sample from organic detritus on a beach

properties.name: Eagle River 2
properties.description: The fossils come from a lens of autochthonous peat exposed near the top of a 3m cutbank section on the east side of the Eagle River.

properties.name: Blow River
properties.description: The fossils come from a cutbank section of the Blow River. The exact location of the site is unknown.

properties.name: Scarborough Bluffs Modern
properties.description: The fossils come from detrital organic stringers interbedded within deltaic silts and sands of the Scarborough Formation exposed in a cliff section facing Lake Ontario at the eastern end of the Scarborough Bluffs. They are underlain by the York Till and overlain by the Sunnybrook, Halton and Wildfield Tills.

properties.name: Cudia Park
properties.description: The fossils come from peaty stringers within the deltaic silts and sands of the Scarborough Formation exposed in a cliff section facing Lake Ontario. The Scarborough Formation is overlain by the Sunnybrook and other tills.

properties.name: Logan's Brickyard
properties.description: The fossils, some of the earliest to be described from North America, come from thin peaty lenses within the deltaic silts and sands of the Scarborough Formation which are overlain by several tills. The fossils came from sections within the former Logan Brick Yard.

properties.name: Reservoir Park
properties.description: The fossils, some of the earliest to be described from North America, come from thin peaty lenses within the deltaic silts and sands of the Scarborough Formation which are overlain by several tills. The fossils came from a section that was exposed during the construction of a reservoir within the city of Toronto in the late 1800's.

properties.name: Mahomet Site
properties.description: The fossils come from peat deposits on the north bank of the Sangamon River near Mahomet. The exact location of the site is unknown. The fossils were initially considered to be of Sangamon age but more probably are from the Robein Member of the Roxana Silt which is Farmdalian mid- to late Wisconsin in age.

properties.name: Narssarssuk
properties.description: The fossil was found in organic detritus from a section in a coastal cliff near the entrance to Wolstenholme Fjord

properties.name: Hellebore Spring
properties.description: Spring

properties.name: Ledge Spring
properties.description: Spring

properties.name: Veg Spring
properties.description: Spring

properties.name: Kuujjuaq
properties.description: The sample was collected from a series of pitfall traps located 500 m from the terminal building at the airport. The habitat was tundra with dwarf spruce. Elias's samples came from a series of habitats in proximity to Fort Chimo (an old name for Kuujjuaq)

properties.name: Anenské údolí
properties.description: Peat bog in a sandstone valley. Physiography: Valley. Surrounding vegetation: Spruce forest.

properties.name: Trelde Klint
properties.description: Lacustrine deposits of interglacial paleolake. Physiography: Basin.

properties.name: Teplické údolí
properties.description: Peat bog. Physiography: Sand stone valley. Surrounding vegetation: Spruce forest.

properties.name: Didachara
properties.description: Poor fen located near the upper forest limit in the Lesser Caucasus (or Caucasus Minor) Mountains of Georgia (41º41'02'N, 42º29'49'E). It sits at the foot of Mt Tsvinta (2423 m) on the NW flank of the Arsiani Range at an elevation of 2000 m a.s.l. The peatland forms part of the headwaters of the Acharistskali River, a tributary of the Chorokhi (Çoruh) River. The summer farms of Didacharis Yayla are nearby.

properties.name: Upper Susitna River Valley
properties.description: Palsa on the southern edge of a small lake just south of the Denali Highway. Surrounding vegetation: Shrub birch, blueberry, and moss are superabundant on the palsa. Cyperaceae and narrow leaf Labrador tea are abundant. Bog rosemary and crowberry are common. In between palsas, Carex is superabundant and Eriophyllum is abundant. Rare Picea dot the hills south of the sampling location.

properties.name: LDDsite11
properties.description: Delorme Site Codes; Land, 1; Physical, 13; Sediment, S; Aquatic, A; Distance From Shore: 0.3

properties.name: Port Kennedy
properties.description: The fossils come from a 45cm thick organic clay at about 14m depth in sinkhole deposits discovered during limestone quarrying operations in the 1870's. Subsequently the quarry became an asbestos dump and is currently undergoing remediation.

properties.name: LDDsite39
properties.description: Delorme Site Codes; Land, 1; Physical, 11; Sediment, S; Aquatic, P; Distance From Shore: 0.3

properties.name: Beaver Creek [ElNq-3]
properties.description: Morlan et al 2001 states, '200-300 m north of the mouth of Beaver Creek, about 12 mi south of Saskatoon.'

properties.name: Bethune [EeNg-6]
properties.description: Site is located on a know NE of Bethune. Burial pit was shallow and disturbed.

properties.name: Benners Estate, North bank of Neuse River
Nunalleq
properties.description: The fossils come from silty peats at depths of 25cm to 1.0m below the surface exposed in shallow excavations. The pits were located along the shoreline of the Bering Sea near the Yup'ik village of Quinhagak.

properties.name: Remus Creek
properties.description: The fossils come from silt and peat of the beaufort Formation exposed in the upper part of the valley of Remus Creek

properties.name: Wolbrom
properties.description: Raised bog.

properties.name: Lake Banyoles
properties.description:
Karstic lake fed by groundwater.
Physiography: subcircular depression with channel.
Surrounding vegetation: Mixed evergreen forests (Quercus ilex, Q. coccifera, Rhamnus alaternus, Phillyrea media, P. angustifolia), deciduous oak stands (Quercus pubescens, Buxus sempervirens, Ilex aquifolium) and Pinus halepensis woodlands. Shrublands.

properties.name: Albufera Alcudia
properties.description: Surrounding vegetation: Halophytes.

properties.name: Cucú cueva

properties.name: Indian Cove E
properties.description: 'Thirty-eight dated packrat middens were collected from upper desert (930-1357m) elevations within Joshua Tree National Park near the ecotone between the Mohave Desert and the Colorado Desert, providing a 30ka record of vegetation change with remarkably even coverage for the last 15ka. (Over 100 midden were collected in the field). This record indicates that vegetation was relatively stable, which may reflect the lack of invasion by extralocal species during the late glacial and the early establishment and persistence of many desert scrub elements. Many of the species found in the modern vegetation assemblages were present by the early Holocene, as indicated by increasing Sorensen's Similarity Index values. C4 grasses and summer-flowering annuals arrived later at Joshua Tree National Park in the early Holocene, suggesting a delayed onset of warm-season monsoonal precipitation compared to other Sonoran Desert and Chihuahuan Desert localities to the east, where summer rains and C4 grasses persisted through the late glacial-interglacial cycle. This would suggest that contemporary flow of monsoonal moisture into eastern California is secondary to the core processes of the North American Monsoon, which remained intact throughout the late Quaternary. In the Holocene, northward displpacement of the jet stream, in both summer and winter, allowed migration of the subtropical ridgeridge as far north as southern Idaho and the advection of monsoonal moisture both westward into eastern California and northward into the southern Great Basin and Colorado Plateau.' (Holmgren et al. 2010: abstract).

properties.name: Saamis [EaOp-6]
properties.description: From CARD: Located in in Medicine Hat, 670 m asl, on two terraces 1.5-3 km upstream from the entrance of Seven Persons Creek into the South Saskatchewan River, Alberta. This late prehistoric site has 5 areas designated A-E. Area B represents campsite activities with a number of basin hearths containing layers of fired rock. Area C is primarily a meat processing area, and Area E is thought to represent butchering and possibly meat processing and killing of bison.

properties.name: Kenney [DjPk-1]
properties.description: Right bank of Pincher Creek, near Brocket, Oldman drainage, Alberta. A multicomponent site with three occupation layers in stratified sequence associated with developed Ah soil horizons. The uppermost, Layer 4, represents an Old Women's phase occupation, while the lower two, Layers 6 and 8, represent the Besant phase. (from CARD)

Located on a terrace or terrace-like surface midway up the north face of the South Saskatchewan River valley, 735 m asl, about 1.5 km north of the present river channel, southeastern Alberta.

properties.name: The Big Lake Bison Kill Site [14RG13]
Waccamaw River, Turkey Creek Oligohaline Marsh
properties.description: Oligohaline marsh at Turkey Creek along the Waccamaw River (salinity 1.49-3.70 ppt). Surrounded by a tidal freshwater forested wetland dominated by Taxodium distichum, Nyssa biflora, and Nyssa aquatica. The vegetation in the oligohaline marsh consists of Typha latifolia, Spartina cynosuroides, Scirpus robustus, and Schoenoplectus montevidensis.

properties.name: Champ Gazon
properties.description: Blanket mire. Physiography: conglomerates on granitic smoothy hills. Surrounding vegetation: forest.

properties.name: Waccamaw River, Turkey Creek, Heavily Salt Impacted Swamp
properties.description: A highly salt-impacted tidal freshwater forested wetland transitioning to an oligohaline marsh at Turkey Creek (salinity 1.49–3.70 ppt). The forested wetland is dominated by Taxodium distichum, Nyssa biflora, and Nyssa aquatica.
